                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "payload": {
                    "id": "socpsy_welcome_text",
                    "markdown": "## Learning Goals\n\nBy the end of this page, students should be able to:\n\n- recognize their professor\n- list some of the topics covered by social psychology.\n\n### Social psychology is everywhere. \n\nYour friendships, your group chats, even your late night scrolling. Who we are and how we treat each other can't be boiled down to a single TikTok trend, or even a single variable in an experiment. \n\n### People are complicated. \n\nThere are always multiple reasons for what we do. In this course, we will use an intersectional lens to examine the richness of our social lives from every angle. Race, gender, age, social class, sexual orientation, and many others. \n\n### Because real life isn't one-dimensional. \n\nWe aren't ever just one thing. Let me give you an example. \n\n### Picture yourself at age seven or eight. \n\nNow imagine you were the only biracial kid in your school photo, with a huge afro, and a strong belief that soon, racism would be a thing of the past. That was me. The epitome of naivety. One weekend, a friend invited me to his home. His family ran a motel. They lived just behind the main office. My mom, who's white, dropped me off. Everything seemed perfectly normal. While playing in the lobby, a Pakistani man pulled in and asked for a room. He was told no rooms were available, even as he pointed out the vacancy sign. My friend's mom said it was a mistake, that they had no more rooms. And I believed her. After all, why would a business owner turn away a customer and lose money? But later, when a white couple arrived, they were given a room immediately. When my dad showed up to pick me up, I heard:\n\n### \"That's your dad?\" \n\nAfter that, I was never invited over again. \n\n### When you hear my story, what explanations pop into your mind? \n\nWould you believe the \"no rooms available\" line? What would you say to your friend the next day at school? This is where social psychology has a lot to say. It explores so many of the processes I witnessed on that day at my friend's motel. \n\n- Prejudice, \n- stereotyping, \n- discrimination, \n- identity, \n- moral reasoning, \n- family conflict, \n- relationships, \n- persuasion, \n- cognitive dissonance. \n\nI found myself asking, \"How could my friend and his family treat people of color so differently?\" The search for that answer inspired my undergraduate thesis and led me to work with social psychologists dedicated to uncovering and reducing implicit biases. And my hope is that this course will challenge you to think critically, to question assumptions, and maybe even launch your own research project."
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
